('computer-science:2-1-2-designing-creating-and-refining-algorithms:tips:1371a296', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-2-designing-creating-and-refining-algorithms', '2.1.2 Designing, Creating and Refining Algorithms', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Writing a clean trace table under exam pressure", "reading": "<p>Trace-table questions are marked <strong>row by row</strong> (or pass by pass), so a slow, organised table scores far better than a fast guess.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Copy the <strong>column headers</strong> the question gives you exactly, in the same order.</li>\n<li>Go through the algorithm <strong>one line at a time</strong>. Only write a new value in a column when that line actually <strong>changes</strong> that variable.</li>\n<li>For a loop, treat each pass as its own row — never merge two passes together or skip a pass \"because it''s obvious\".</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you lose track, restart the trace from the beginning rather than guessing the rest — a fully correct restart earns more marks than a table that goes wrong halfway through.</p>", "question": "In a trace table, when should you write a new value in a variable''s column?", "options": ["Only on the exact line where that variable''s value actually changes", "On every single line of the algorithm you are given, regardless of whether it changes anything at all", "Only once, right at the very end of the whole algorithm", "Only when the algorithm prints something to the screen"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A trace table column only gets a new entry when that specific line changes the variable — not on every line, and not just once at the end."}'::jsonb),
